as two lobes and left lung has three lobes","Both lungs have two lobes","Both lungs have three lobes","Both lungs have four lobes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct anatomical arrangement is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright lung has three lobes and left lung has two lobes\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). The right lung is divided into upper, middle and lower lobes by two fissures - the oblique and horizontal fissures. The left lung has only upper and lower lobes separated by the oblique fissure. The left lung has less volume than the right due to the cardiac notch, which accommodates the heart. This asymmetry is reflected in the different lobar arrangements between the two lungs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The right lung has three lobes (upper, middle, lower) while the left lung has two lobes (upper, lower).","The oblique fissure separates the upper and lower lobes in both lungs.","The horizontal fissure separates the upper and middle lobes of the right lung only.","The left lung has less volume due to the cardiac notch accommodating the heart."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cLungs diagram with internal details\u201d by Patrick J. Lynch\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 2.5 Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.5). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Lungs_diagram_detailed.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18632"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21432"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21432"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/h7Ljz